│ "thoughts": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe `loop-vectorize` pass is aborting due   │
│ to an assertion failure in `LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF`. The assertion        │
│ `(BestFactor.Width == LegacyVF.Width || planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(...)) &&     │
│ \"VPlan cost model and legacy cost model disagreed\"` indicates a discrepancy between the  │
│ vectorization factor (VF) chosen by the new VPlan-based cost model and the legacy cost     │
│ model. This usually happens when the two models have different assumptions or              │
│ capabilities, and the code fails to account for this difference.\n\n### 2. Analyzing       │
│ `opt`'s Log\n\nThe `opt` log shows that the loop contains a reduction-like                 │
│ pattern:\n```llvm\n%or13 = phi i32 [ 0, %entry ], [ %or, %loop ]\n%and = and i32 %or13,    │
│ 1\n%or = or i32 %and, %conv\n```\nHere, `%or13` is an `i32` but is immediately narrowed by │
│ the `and i32 %or13, 1` instruction before being used in the `or` operation. This           │
│ \"narrowed reduction\" is a key feature of the reproducer. The Scalar Evolution analysis   │
│ correctly identifies the range of `%or13` as `[0, 2)`, but the loop's trip count is        │
│ unknown.\n\nThe crash occurs after analysis, during the cost-modeling phase where the      │
│ vectorizer decides *if* and *how* to vectorize the loop. The failing assertion is a        │
│ consistency check between two different cost models.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nBy   │
│ inspecting the state in the debugger, we can determine the differing decisions of the two  │
│ cost models:\n- The VPlan-based model, which is the future of the vectorizer, chooses not  │
│ to vectorize, resulting in `BestFactor.Width` being 1 (scalar execution).\n- The legacy    │
│ cost model decides that vectorizing is profitable, selecting a vectorization factor of 4,  │
│ so `LegacyVF.Width` is 4.\n\nThe core of the problem lies in how the legacy cost model     │
│ handles this specific \"narrowed reduction\" pattern. The function                         │
│ `LoopVectorize::getReductionCost` is responsible for estimating the cost of vectorizing    │
│ reductions. For this `or` reduction, it eventually calls                                   │
│ `TTI->getArithmeticReductionCost`.\n\nInside `getArithmeticReductionCost`, there is logic  │
│ to handle reductions on narrowed types. It checks if the reduction operation is on a type  │
│ that is wider than necessary. In our case, the `or` is on `i32`, but the values are known  │
│ to be either 0 or 1. The code attempts to \"re-legalize\" the reduction on a smaller type  │
│ (`i8` in this case) to see if it would be cheaper.\n\nThe bug is in the condition that     │
│ triggers this re-legalization:\n```cpp\n//                                                 │
│ llvm/lib/Analysis/TargetTransformInfo.cpp:1006\nif (Opcode == Instruction::Or &&\n         │
│ (isa<ConstantInt>(Op->getOperand(0)) ||\n     isa<ConstantInt>(Op->getOperand(1))))        │
