│ the reproducer, the `or` instruction is `%or = or i32 %and, %conv`. Neither `%and` nor     │
│ `%conv` are `ConstantInt`s; `%conv` is a `zext` of a function argument, and `%and` is the  │
│ result of a previous instruction. Therefore, this condition is false.\n\nHowever, the      │
│ values are indeed narrow. `%conv` is either 0 or 1, and `%and` is also 0 or 1. The legacy  │
│ cost model fails to recognize this, and proceeds to calculate the cost for a full `i32`    │
│ reduction, which it deems profitable. The VPlan cost model, being more modern and precise, │
│ correctly identifies that vectorizing this loop is not beneficial (possibly due to the     │
│ overhead of managing the reduction) and chooses a scalar plan.\n\nThe fix is to relax the  │
│ check in `getArithmeticReductionCost`. Instead of requiring a `ConstantInt` operand, we    │
│ should check if the operands have a known narrow bit-width using `isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo`. │
│ This correctly identifies that the operands are effectively narrow, allowing the cost      │
│ model to properly evaluate the cost of the narrowed reduction. This change makes the       │
│ legacy cost model's decision align with the VPlan model, resolving the assertion           │
│ failure.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix involves modifying the condition in   │
│ `getArithmeticReductionCost` to correctly identify operands with a narrow effective        │
│ bit-width.\n\n```cpp\n// llvm/lib/Analysis/TargetTransformInfo.cpp\n\n// Edit point        │
│ 1\n1006,1008 ->\n    if (Opcode == Instruction::Or &&\n                                    │
│ (isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(Op->getOperand(0), DL, 0, &AC, CtxI, DT) ||\n                      │
│ isKnownToBeAPowerOfTwo(Op->getOperand(1), DL, 0, &AC, CtxI, DT))) {\n\n```\n\n### 5.       │
│ Conclusion\n\nThe root cause of the assertion failure was a discrepancy between the VPlan  │
│ and legacy cost models, caused by the legacy model's failure to correctly identify a       │
│ \"narrowed reduction\". By improving the detection logic in `getArithmeticReductionCost`,  │
│ the legacy model's cost estimation becomes more accurate and aligns with the VPlan model's │
│ decision. This prevents the assertion from firing and allows the vectorizer to correctly   │
│ decide against vectorizing this specific loop, which is the more profitable choice."})     │
